bug.short_desc: missing approval (requirements) are not shown in review editor with Gerrit 2.4 and later

long_desc.thetext: Dopes this mean that "our" copy of ChangeDetail -- that is, com.google.gerrit.common jar -- needs to be updated? I'm not sure how we update this? Do we need to do new CQ for latest com.google.gerrit bundle or what?
No, we simply extend it and add what we need. That is what ChangeDetailX is for.

Ah. I wasn't sure what was going on there, and it isn't at all clear to me how this is retrieved from the API. Presumably the values are injected somehow.
Steffen, could you put in a review just for these data changes? Then I can take care of the rest of this task and it will be more clear how to maintain this in the future.
Just add a data structure to the class that matches the JSON above and it should work.

Actually, it seems that we can just infer the missing ones by getting the set of global config approvals, removing those that have been approved, and returning the results as the needed approvals. Does anyone see a problem with that approach? The only think I can think of is that there might be approvals that aren't needed, and there are some extra semantics in Label Status, but I don't see anything that we need for UI. I don't want to clutter up the model otherwise.
Steffen, I'd also like a little background on the Gerrit JSON stuff. Why aren't we simply getting the latest source code and updating that directly from model? Is it simply too much trouble or is there something more going on here?
Ok. To answer my own question, I realized that that information cannot be inferred, because it's rule driven and repository specific. So we'll do it this way.

In the current (broken) implementation, it looks like it is intended that the requirements status be shown, e.g. something like:
Code Review -2 Verified +1
etc..
But the current gerrit API doesn't provide that -- it just gives whether it is is needed or not. Given that, it seems sort of silly to have a seperate requirements section.
I'd like to move this into the "Approvals" section and do something a little more simple/clean. One thought is to add a "Status" row to the current Reviewers table, with an appropriate icon for OK, NEED... etc..
Thoughts?

(In reply to comment #5) > Steffen, I'd also like a little background on the Gerrit JSON stuff. Why aren't > we simply getting the latest source code and updating that directly from model? > Is it simply too much trouble or is there something more going on here?
We would loose compatibility with older version. Also the process involves CQs, updating Orbit bundles etc. and hence is a lot of effort. Simply adding a new type and a field is much more simple.
I don't have a problem with changing the UI as long as it's clear what votes are required. To some degree that seems like a separate effort though. You'll need to update the data model in any case to retrieve the relevant information from Gerrit.

(In reply to comment #8) > I don't have a problem with changing the UI as long as it's clear what votes are > required. To some degree that seems like a separate effort though. You'll need > to update the data model in any case to retrieve the relevant information from > Gerrit.
Yeah, the actual issue is that AFAICT the new data model doesn't have the information we need to do what I think it used to do. :) I think it's reasonable to fix the UI under this bug as well, given we can't recover the existing UI anyway. But we can recover exactly what the current Web UI shows.
What we have now is a "requirements" section which shows a simple list of the required fields:
_Reviewers_
Verified Code Review Mylyn Test User -1
_Requirements_ Code Review Verified
Which again is kind of silly.
I propose for now we just do something like:
_Reviewers_
Verified Code Review Mylyn Test User -1
Need Verified Need Code Review
I'm not sure what to do to provide a decent visual separation between the two, though. The Web Ui has a table format, but that's cluttered and unneccsary. Ideas?
Or, to make things more elegant by having a summation row or highlighting the missing columns in some other way. (Oddly though, the Submit records data doesn't seem to provide the OK status, it only gives NEEDED so we'd have to assume that those columns without a NEED were satisfied.)

Sure, if it's easy enough let's improve the UI. Have you considered showing icons as part of the header, i.e. decorate each of the categories with an icon rather than adding an extra line?

I did, but I was thinking that it might look sort of crowded/jumbled. But I don't like the placement at the bottom row either, and the top row would probably not be better... I'll give it a try.
I also considered using plain text, or a mix of plain text and icons, but I'm not sure that we can assume what that text would be, as it is dependent on the Gerrit rules on the server. We don't get e.g. +1, -2.. OTOH it's sort of weird, because if you look at the columns in the Derrit Web UI review list, they have a red X for rejected (-2), a -1 for needs (??), and a green check for approved (+2). And then there is a green +1 but that information isn't provided by submit records at all..
